The Atiku Centre for Leadership, American University of Nigeria (AUN), has commenced Transactional Radio Instructions (TRI), program for 500,000 pupils in Adamawa and Gombe states. The University President, Dawn Dekle, said the program comprises  of four components of sound, pedagogy stories, songs, syschronized workbooks which  seeks to get learners connect with lesson as  radio drama series accompanied by easy to memorise songs. Prof Abbah Tahir, Vice President for University Relations said the pilot program funded by the USAID is to strengthen the education system through capacity development with the continued closure of schools due to COVID-19 pandemic in the Northeast. Tahir added that, the institution pioneered the TELA project (Technology Enhanced Learning for All), which empowered nearly 20,000 underprivileged children, mainly Almajiris and youngsters from IDP families, who were fleeing the epicenter of insurgency in the region. Audi Liman, Chief of party said, SENSE is working with ministry of education, SUBEB, LGEA and national and international academic institutions as partners to improve educational outcomes for 200,000 primary school children The program expected to improve the reaching skills of 5,000 teachers with additional support for female teachers. It intend reaching out to 200 primary schools and improve education management capacity of 100; education managers. Dr Grace Malgwi, in her remark enumerated that SENSE is collaborating with state Better Education Service Delivery (BESDA), ensure all outreach  to cover the state. State deputy Governor Crowther Seth said government declared free education to eliminate out of school children in the state. 